value.value: A questionnaire designed to assess beliefs that people have concerning doctors, patients, and medical care.

label.value: Doctor Should Decide What Gets Talked About During Visit

value.value: A question about whether the doctor is the one who should decide what gets talked about during a visit.

label.value: Health Care is Less Personal but Pays for Medical Advances

value.value: A question about whether health care is less personal these days, but a small price to pay for medical advances.
The inspection of one's own body, usually for signs of disease.

label.value: Most Important Part of Standard Medical Visit is Physical Exam

value.value: A question about whether the most important part of a standard medical visit is the physical exam.

label.value: Often Best for Patients to Not Have Full Explanation of Medical Condition

value.value: A question about whether it is often best for patients if they do not have a full explanation of their medical condition.

label.value: Patient Should Rely on Doctor's Knowledge and Not Find Out About Their Conditions

value.value: A question about whether patients should rely on their doctor's knowledge and not try to find out about their conditions on their own.

label.value: Doctors Asking Lots of Questions About Patient's Background is Prying into Personal Matters

value.value: A question about whether when doctors ask a lot of questions about patient's background, they are prying too much into personal matters.

label.value: If Doctors are Good at Diagnosis and Treatment then their Relations with Patients Not Important

value.value: A question about if doctors are truly good at diagnosis and treatment, the way they relate to patients is not that important.

label.value: Many Patients Continue Asking Questions When Not Learning Anything New

value.value: A question about whether many patients continue asking questions even though they are not learning anything new.

label.value: Patients Should be Treated as Equal Partners with Doctor

value.value: A question about whether patients should be treated as if they were partners with their doctor, equal in power and status.

label.value: Patients Generally Want Reassurance Rather than Information about Health

value.value: A question about whether patients generally want reassurance rather than information about their health.

label.value: If Doctor's Primary Tools are being Open and Warm, Doctor Will Not Have Success

value.value: A question about if a doctor's primary tools are being open and warm, the doctor will not have a lot of success.

label.value: Disagreement is Sign that Doctor Does Not Have Patient's Respect and Trust

value.value: A question about whether when patients disagree with their doctor, this is a sign that the doctor does not have the patient's respect and trust.
Surgical reconstruction of the breast.

label.value: Treatment Plan Cannot Succeed if in Conflict with Patient's Lifestyle or Values

value.value: A question about whether a treatment plan cannot succeed if it is in conflict with a patient's lifestyle or values.

label.value: Most Patients Want to Get in and Out of Doctor's Office as Quickly as Possible

value.value: A question about whether most patients want to get in and get out of the doctor's office as quickly as possible.

label.value: Patient Must Always be Aware that Doctor is in Charge

value.value: A question about whether the patient must always be aware that the doctor is in charge.

label.value: Not Important to Know Patient's Culture and Background to Treat their Illness

value.value: A question about whether it is not important that a doctor know a patient's culture and background in order to treat the person's illness.

label.value: Humor is Major Ingredient in Doctor's Treatment of Patient

value.value: A question about whether humor is a major ingredient in the doctor's treatment of the patient.

label.value: When Patients Look up Medical Information This Confuses More than Helps

value.value: A question about whether when patients look up medical information on their own, it usually confuses more than it helps.
A response indicating moderate disagreement.
A response indicating moderate agreement.
Immune cells that have left the bloodstream and migrated into a tumor.

label.value: Ultra High Sensitivity C-Reactive Protein Measurement

value.value: The determination of the amount of C-reactive protein (CRP) present in a sample, usually serum from a blood draw from a subject that does not have a chronic inflammatory condition, through the use of an enhanced particle-enhanced immunoturbidimetric assay. This test is optimized to measure lower concentrations of CRP than a conventional CRP test. Accuracy is enhanced to ultra high levels through the use of a proprietary set of calibrated CRP samples.
Treatment with a radioactive substance that is linked to an antibody so that it will attach to a tumor when injected into the body.
The collection of microorganisms existing in the urinary tract and/or urine of an organism.
A semiquantitative finding indicating that the concentration of 25-hydroxyvitamin D2 plus 25-hydroxyvitamin D3 is less than 66 ng/mL.
A semiquantitative finding indicating that the concentration of 25-hydroxyvitamin D2 plus 25-hydroxyvitamin D3 is less than 30 ng/mL.
The highest rate of oxygen consumption a subject reaches during an aerobic capacity test.

A resilience-building intervention program for adolescents and young adults with serious illness. It focuses of 4 disease-non-specific skills: stress management, goal-setting and problem-solving, positive re-appraisals of stressors, and meaning-making or benefit-finding.
Indicates that expression of WT1 has not been detected in a sample.
A change in the nucleotide sequence of the XPO1 gene.

label.value: Bone Marrow Blasts Decreased by 50 Percent or More Compared to Pretreatment Level

value.value: A semiquantitative finding indicating that the amount of immature mononuclear cells in a subject's sample of nucleated cells from bone marrow has decreased by 50 percent or more over the value recorded for a pretreatment sample from that subject.

A post-translationally modified form of focal adhesion kinase 1 (FAK; FAK1; PTK2) where the tyrosine (Y; Tyr) at residue 397 is phosphorylated. Cell adhesion-signaling promotes the association of FAK with Src family kinases, which stimulates autophosphorylation of FAK Y397 and creates a SH2-binding site on FAK to promote Src family kinase- and integrin-mediated signaling.
Describes cells, tissues, conditions, or diseases that are responsive to or dependent on any of the androgen hormones.

Surgical removal of part of the pancreas, duodenum, and distal part of the bile duct.  Sometimes, the lower portion of the stomach and the gallbladder are also removed.  This procedure is performed for pancreatic, ampullary, duodenal and distal bile duct cancers.
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to any translocation involving Xp11.2 on the short arm of the X chromosome.
An indication that amplification of the EGFR gene was not detected in a sample.
A genetic finding indicating that DNA methylation in the promoter region of the MGMT gene has been detected in a sample.
A tool designed to assess the degree of control an individual wants to assume when decisions are being made about medical treatment.

label.value: Preference for Making Decisions about Health Care

value.value: A question about an individual's preference for making decisions about their healthcare.

label.value: Prefer to Make Decision About Which Treatment I Will Receive

value.value: A response indicating that an individual prefers to make the decisions about their treatment.

An injectable magnesium oxide-based bone void filler (BVF) with potential osteoconductive properties. Upon injection into bony voids or defects, the magnesium-based BVF mimics cancellous bone and provides a supportive scaffold to facilitate the bone healing process. Magnesium contributes to the structural development of bone and may potentially increase proliferation of bone marrow stromal cells and improve attachment and growth of osteoblasts.
The reemergence of acinic cell breast carcinoma after a period of remission.
The reemergence of pancreatic acinar cell carcinoma after a period of remission.
Surgical removal of part or all of the esophagus.
The reemergence of prostate acinar adenocarcinoma after a period of remission.

label.value: Recurrent Parotid Gland Acinic Cell Carcinoma

value.value: The reemergence of parotid gland acinic cell carcinoma after a period of remission.

label.value: Recurrent Submandibular Gland Acinic Cell Carcinoma

value.value: The reemergence of submandibular gland acinic cell carcinoma after a period of remission.
